<?xml version="1.0"?>
<rdf:RDF xmlns="https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#"
     xml:base="https://w3id.org/beast/ontology"
     xmlns:owl="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#"
     xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#"
     xmlns:xml="http://www.w3.org/XML/1998/namespace"
     xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#"
     xmlns:prov="http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#"
     xmlns:rdfs="http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#"
     xmlns:skos="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#"
     xmlns:vann="http://purl.org/vocab/vann/"
     xmlns:terms="http://purl.org/dc/terms/"
     xmlns:schema="https://schema.org/"
     xmlns:ontology="https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#">
    <owl:Ontology rdf:about="https://w3id.org/beast/ontology">
        <terms:bibliographicCitation xml:lang="en">Gamboa Nivia, M.J., Pinto, M., Roggiani, S., Spadavecchia, A. (2026). BEAST Ontology. https://w3id.org/beast/ontology</terms:bibliographicCitation>
        <terms:created rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date">2026-05-01</terms:created>
        <terms:creator>Alice Spadavecchia</terms:creator>
        <terms:creator>Maria Juliana Gamboa Nivia</terms:creator>
        <terms:creator>Miriana Pinto</terms:creator>
        <terms:creator>Sara Roggiani</terms:creator>
        <terms:description xml:lang="en">An ontology for the description of creatures, their provenance, biological components and symbolic meanings.</terms:description>
        <terms:license rdf:resource="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"/>
        <terms:publisher rdf:resource="https://github.com/hexWitches"/>
        <terms:references>Durand, G. (1972). Le Strutture Antropologiche dell&apos;Immaginario: introduzione all&apos;archetipologia generale</terms:references>
        <terms:title xml:lang="en">BEAST Ontology</terms:title>
        <vann:preferredNamespacePrefix>beast</vann:preferredNamespacePrefix>
        <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">The BEAST ontology is structured into three interconnected modules. The Provenance Module documents the historical and textual footprint of creatures, distinguishing between the universal concept of a beast (Creature) and its source-specific manifestations (Interpretation) across bestiaries, literary works, visual artworks, and cinematic works; it also tracks the diachronic evolution of creature terminology through Nomenclature and Etymology. The Biological Module defines the morphological and behavioural traits of both real and imaginary beings: it catalogs anatomical composition, habitats, diets, and abilities, and documents anomalies in real animals through a structured vocabulary of absence, duplication, and modification. The Symbolic Module provides a multidimensional framework for the analysis of creatures as cultural and archetypal figures. It integrates two analytical layers: Gilbert Durand&apos;s anthropological structures of the imaginary (DurandImaginary scheme) and an archetype and narrative function layer that distinguishes the universal psychological patterns creatures embody from the contextual roles they perform in specific sources. Together the three modules enable the ontology to trace a creature from its historical attestation in a primary text, through its biological description, to its deepest symbolic resonance in the collective imagination.</rdfs:comment>
        <schema:codeRepository rdf:resource="https://github.com/hexWitches/beast"/>
    </owl:Ontology>
    


